            <section class="prose text-sm">
              <h2>What is ABSI (A Body Shape Index)?</h2>
              <p>
                A Body Shape Index (ABSI) is an anthropometric measure proposed
                by Krakauer and Krakauer (2012) to better capture
                <strong>central obesity</strong> – how much fat is stored around
                your waist – relative to your overall body size. Unlike BMI,
                which only uses height and weight, ABSI also includes
                <strong>waist circumference</strong>.
              </p>
              <p>
                In large population studies, higher ABSI values were associated
                with a higher risk of death, even after adjusting for BMI. That
                means two people with the same BMI can have different ABSI
                values and different levels of risk, depending on where they
                store fat.
              </p>

              <h2>ABSI formula</h2>
              <p>ABSI is defined as:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="mb-1 text-gray-800"><strong>Step 1 – BMI</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{BMI} = \dfrac{\text{weight (kg)}}{\text{height
                  (m)}^2}\)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-3 mb-1 text-gray-800">
                  <strong>Step 2 – ABSI</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{ABSI} = \dfrac{\text{waist (m)}}{\text{BMI}^{2/3}
                  \times \text{height (m)}^{1/2}}\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The units of ABSI are unconventional
                (m<sup>11/6</sup>·kg<sup>−2/3</sup>). For interpretation,
                researchers usually convert ABSI to a
                <strong>z-score</strong> relative to a reference population of
                the same age and sex.
              </p>

              <h3>How this calculator estimates ABSI z-score</h3>
              <p>
                The original ABSI research used large US datasets to compute
                age‑ and sex‑specific means and standard deviations. Because we
                do not collect or store your personal data, this tool uses a
                <strong>simplified approximation</strong>:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  We assume a typical adult ABSI mean of 0.080 and standard
                  deviation of 0.005.
                </li>
                <li>
                  We compute an approximate z-score as: \(z \approx (\text{ABSI}
                  - 0.080) / 0.005\).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Risk categories are then assigned based on this z-score.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This is <strong>not</strong> a substitute for a full clinical
                risk model, but it gives you a sense of how your body shape
                compares to an average adult.
              </p>

              <h2>How to measure your waist correctly</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>Stand upright, relax, and breathe out normally.</li>
                <li>
                  Find the midpoint between the bottom of your ribs and the top
                  of your hip bones (iliac crest).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Wrap a flexible tape measure around this point, keeping it
                  horizontal and snug but not compressing the skin.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Record the measurement to the nearest 0.5 cm or 0.25 inch.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                Consistent technique matters: small errors in waist measurement
                can noticeably change ABSI.
              </p>

              <h2>ABSI vs BMI vs waist-to-height ratio</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>BMI</strong> reflects total body mass relative to
                  height, but does not distinguish fat from muscle or fat
                  distribution.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Waist-to-height ratio</strong> is a simple indicator
                  of central fat; keeping your waist below half your height is
                  often recommended.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>ABSI</strong> mathematically adjusts waist for both
                  BMI and height, isolating how “waist‑heavy” your body shape
                  is.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                In practice, it is useful to look at all three together. For
                example, a normal BMI but high ABSI and waist‑to‑height ratio
                may still indicate increased cardiometabolic risk.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and medical disclaimer</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  ABSI was developed and validated mainly in adult populations;
                  it is <strong>not intended for children</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Ethnicity, body composition, fitness level and underlying
                  health conditions can all modify risk.
                </li>
                <li>
                  ABSI does not replace clinical assessment, lab tests or
                  imaging.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                <strong
                  >This calculator is for educational purposes only and does not
                  provide medical advice, diagnosis or treatment.</strong
                >
                Always consult your doctor or another qualified health
                professional with questions about your health or before making
                major lifestyle changes.
              </p>
